        <b><span id="titleLabel">1.6 - Massively cross-platform: Closing in on the dream of one game, many platforms</span></b>
        <table border="1" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="dateTimeLabel">Thursday, May 11, 11:30 AM - 1:00 PM</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="roomLabel">Room 404AB</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="descriptionLabel">For years, developers, publishers, and gamers have talked about getting game terminals talking to each other, regardless of their platform. While not easy, opening up a single, persistent gameworld to PC, console, and portable gamers is now within reach. Taking the first real steps was Final Fantasy XI, which linked PlayStation 2 and PC gamers. Recently, that title opened its gameworld to Xbox 360 gamers as well. While FFXI may have been the first title to offer this level of cross-platform gaming, it won't be the last. Developers are designing the infrastructure that will link gamers on home terminals seamlessly with each other as well as with gamers on the go. This session will focus on where the industry stands today in enabling massively cross-platform (MCP) games. What are the remaining technical challenges? How will MCP games change the consumer experience? And how will MCP games alter the relationship between the publisher, developer, and platform owner? Hear how designers, publishers, and technologists are preparing for MCP games, and find out how soon they will become the norm.</span></td>
            </tr>
